
Discovering Roy Bhaskar's East-West Integration

http://www.raggedclaws.com/criticalrealism/archive/rbhaskar_rbi.html

Michel Bauwens: "Readers of my critique of Ken Wilber, are aware that my sympathies for integral and integrative projects remain strong. Though Roy Bhaskar has been writing for over twenty years, I only recently read a first book by him, on the Enlightenment and the continuing importance of human emancipation. It was pretty much `love at first sight'. Here's a theory that takes stock of the emancipatory tradition, is rooted in scientific research, but also recently integrated the findings of the Eastern world.

'''The book I've been reading is: From Science to Emancipation: Alienation and the Actuality of the Enlightenment.''' Though somewhat poorly edited, it's a readable collection of introductory essays, interviews, lectures and dialogues, covering both his early (critical realism as a philosophy of science), middle (updated dialectics as the study of process and change) and later (integrating eastern thought) evolution."

